{
  "texts": [
    "At its core, ADL-LLM transforms raw sensor data into natural language sentences describing the high-level events observed in the home.",
    "ADL-LLM uses a specifically designed prompting strategy to query the LLM about the most likely ADL performed by the subject.",
    "Despite ADL-LLM does not require training data, we show that a small labeled dataset can further improve the recognition rate thanks to a few-shot prompting mechanism.The main contributions of this paper are the following:• We propose ADL-LLM, a novel LLM-based method for zero-shot sensor-based ADL recognition in smart home environments.",
    "• Our results on two public datasets show that zero-shot ADL-LLM reaches recognition rates comparable (and sometimes better) than standard supervised approaches.• We extend ADL-LLM to perform few-shot prompting when a small labeled dataset is available, by leveraging a semantic-based example selection strategy.",
    "Our experiments show that few-shot ADL-LLM outperforms standard supervised approaches in labeled data scarcity scenarios.We provide the source code implementing our system to make our results reproduciblefoot_0.2 Related Work Data Scarcity in Human Activity RecognitionThe labeled data scarcity problem in Human Activity Recognition (HAR) is one of the major challenges limiting large-scale real deployments, and several research groups have been working on this problem for several years."
  ]
}